{"id":"2212.10904","submitter":"Thomas Sawczuk","authors":"Thomas Sawczuk, Anna Palczewska, Ben Jones, Jan Palczewski","title":"A Bayesian Mixture Model Approach to Expected Possession Values in Rugby\n  League","comments":"22 pages including appendices, 3 tables, 5 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"stat.AP","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  The aim of this study was to improve previous zonal approaches to expected\npossession value (EPV) models in low data availability sports by introducing a\nBayesian Mixture Model approach to an EPV model in rugby league. 99,966\nobservations from the 2021 Super League season were used. A set of 33 centres\n(30 in the field of play, 3 in the try area) were located across the pitch.\nEach centre held the probability of five possession outcomes occurring\n(converted/unconverted try, penalty, drop goal and no points). Weights for the\nmodel were provided for each location on the pitch using linear and bilinear\ninterpolation techniques. Probabilities at each centre were estimated using a\nBayesian approach and extrapolated to all locations on the pitch. An EPV\nmeasure was derived from the possession outcome probabilities and their points\nvalue. The model produced a smooth pitch surface, which was able to provide\ndifferent possession outcome probabilities and EPVs for every location on the\npitch. Differences between team attacking and defensive plots were visualised\nand an actual vs expected player rating system was developed. The model\nprovides significantly more flexibility than previous approaches and could be\nadapted to other sports where data is similarly sparse.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 21 Dec 2022 10:26:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-22"}
